> By coincidence, our project ran into the same issue just now, when we noticed .text doesn't return the textual representation of a link in cases where the cell included rich text formatting. Instead, the above occurs. Would be grateful if there were a dependable way to access the textual content of the cell that we wouldn't need to double check.

---
@ajuvonen Are there any test files and test code to reproduce this error?

Haven't been able to produce a similar file myself yet, and can't share the original due to confidentiality. Simplified code that shows how our files are handled
```
//fileContents is uploaded by user via file input
const logFirstCell = async (fileContents) => {
  const workbook = new ExcelJS.workbook();
  await workbook.xlsx.load(fileContents);
  console.log(workbook.worksheets[0].getCell('A1').text); // assuming the problematic cell is first cell of first sheet
